It is obvious that a ruler holding a ‘ proconsulare imperium’ valid within the pomoerium ⁷ had already what was most important in the consular power, and Augustus showed no desire for the accumulation of empty titles. It would seem, however, possible that the decree which Dio appears to quote may have given something more than mere con- sular insignia. The conception of the princeps as the chief magistrate of the state, implied in many powers exercised by Augustus and his successors, might not impossibly have been represented by a consular power or certain specified powers under that name; the more so, as such power might be conceived by a fiction as comprehending functions of other magistracies, as those of censor, praetor, or curule aedile, originally included in the consulship.
